About Dataset

  • Datasource[Kaggle]: https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/thedevastator/higher-education-predictors-of-student-retention
  • This dataset provides data on undergraduate students, including their demographics, socioeconomic status, and academic performance, with the aim of investigating the influence of these factors on student dropout rates and academic success. Additionally, the data will be used to build a machine learning model to predict whether a student is likely to drop out or not.
  • Marital status
  • Application mode
  • Application order
  • Course
  • Daytime/evening attendance
  • Previous qualification
  • Nationality
  • Motherâ€™s qualification
  • Fatherâ€™s qualification
  • Motherâ€™s occupation
  • Fatherâ€™s occupation
  • Displacement status
  • Educational special needs
  • Debtor status
  • Tuition fees up to date status
  • Gender
  • Scholarship holder status
  • Age at enrollment
  • International student status
  • Number of curricular units credited, enrolled, evaluated, and approved in the first semester.

1.2 Replace Enrolled with Graduate

  • I decided to combine the Enrolled and Graduate categories and renamed it as â€œGraduateâ€ to simplify the analysis.
  • This information is crucial as it provides insights into the overall distribution of student outcomes and serves as a baseline for subsequent analysis.
  • Understanding the distribution of the outcome variable is an essential first step in any analysis, as it helps to inform subsequent analysis and interventions aimed at improving student retention rates in undergraduate programs.

2. Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA)

2.1 Load Library

library(ggplot2)
library(corrplot)
library(gridExtra)
library(psych)
library(reshape2)

2.2 Distribution of the target variable

  • The resulting table of the outcome variable showed that there are 1421 dropouts and 3003 graduates, with a dropout rate of approximately 32%.
ggplot(ac, aes(x = Target)) + 
  geom_bar(stat = "count", aes(fill = Target)) + 
  geom_text(stat='count', aes(label=after_stat(count)), vjust=-0.5)+
  labs(title = "Distribution of Target")

2.3 Distribution of Socioeconomic Factor Variables

  • The socioeconomic factor variables (such as GDP, Inflation Rate, and Unemployment Rate) are equally distributed between students who dropped out and those who graduated.
  • However, there are outliers in the distribution of mother/father occupation and age at enrollment.
macro_boxplot <- ac[, c("Target",
                        "MaritalStatus",
                        "MotherQual", 
                        "FatherQual",
                        "MotherOccu",
                        "FatherOccu",
                        "AgeEnroll",
                        "UnempRate",
                        "InflationRate",
                        "GDP")]

macro_melt <- melt(macro_boxplot, id.vars = "Target")

ggplot(macro_melt, aes(x = Target, y = value, fill = Target)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  facet_wrap(~ variable, scales = "free") +
  labs(title = "Distribution of Socioeconomic Factor Variables", y = "")

2.4 Distribution of Age

  • The data pertains to undergraduate students, and the majority falls between the age range of 18 to 23.
  • Students between the ages of 25 to 30 are more likely to drop out than to graduate.
  • Age ranges between 50 to 70 exhibit outliers in the data.
ggplot(ac, aes(x = `AgeEnroll`, fill = Target)) +
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 1, alpha = 0.5, position = "identity") +
  labs(title = "Distribution of Age at Enrollment by Target", x = "Age at Enrollment", y = "Count") +
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("#B2182B", "#00BFFF"))

2.5 Distribution of Curricular Units: 1St Semester

  • The curricular unit variables in the first semester are highly correlated (as seen in the correlation matrix later).
  • The number of curricular units credited, evaluated, and approved in the first semester are all strongly associated with student dropout rates, with the highest dropout rates occurring in the first semester credited followed by evaluation and approval.
curricular1_boxplot <- ac[, c("Target", 
                              "FirSemCredit", 
                              "FirSemEnroll", 
                              "FirSemEval", 
                              "FirSemApprove", 
                              "FirSemGrade", 
                              "FirSemNoEval")]

curricular1_melt <- melt(curricular1_boxplot, id.vars = "Target")

ggplot(curricular1_melt, aes(x = Target, y = value, fill = Target)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  facet_wrap(~ variable, scales = "free") +
  labs(title = "Distribution of Curricular Units: 1St Semester", y = "")

2.6 First Semester Grade by Target

  • Higher first semester grade generally correlates with a higher likelihood of graduating.
  • However, some students with relatively high grades (between 10-15) still drop out.
ggplot(ac, aes(x = FirSemGrade, fill = Target)) + 
  geom_density(alpha = 0.4) + 
  labs(title = "Density Plots of First Semester Grade by Target")

2.7 Distribution of Curricular Units: 2nd Semester

  • The distribution of curricular units for the second semester is similar to the first semester.
  • As with the first semester, the grade is the most significant factor contributing to student dropout, followed by approval and evaluation.
curricular2_boxplot <- ac[, c("Target", 
                              "SecSemCredit", 
                              "SecSemEnroll",

2.8 Second Semester Enrolled by Target

  • Students who are enrolled in 5 to 7 curricular units tend to drop out more often than those who are enrolled in fewer or more units.
  • Among students who graduated, the majority are enrolled in 7 curricular units, and some students are enrolled in more than 7 units but still managed to graduate.
ggplot(ac, aes(x =SecSemEnroll, fill = Target)) + 
  geom_density(alpha = 0.4) + 
  labs(title = "Density Plots of Second Semester Enrolled by Target")

2.9 Distribution of Binary Social Facotrs

  • Evening class attendance is associated with a higher rate of dropout.
  • Students requiring special education are more likely to drop out.
  • Non-scholarship recipients have a higher likelihood of dropping out.
  • Domestic students have a higher dropout rate compared to international students.
binary_count <- ac[, c("Target", "DayNight", "SpecialEdu", "Debtor", "TuitionFees", 
             "Gender", "Scholarship", "International")]

binary_melt <- melt(binary_count, id.vars = "Target")

ggplot(binary_melt, aes(x = value, fill = Target)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "count", position = "dodge") +
  facet_wrap(~ variable, scales = "free") +
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = c(0, 1))+
  labs(title = "Frequency Histogram of Binary Binary Social Facotrs", x = "Value", y = "Count", fill = "Target")

2.10 Corre_Matrix of variables

  • There is multicollinearity among variables such as curricular units in the first and second semesters, grades, and approvals.
  • The family variables, including father/motherâ€™s qualifications and occupation, also show high correlation (possibly multicollinearity).
  • With a large number of variables, itâ€™s difficult to see the details, so we may need to come back and recheck after reducing the number of variables.

3.4 Check for Multicollinearity

  • There is severe multicollinearity as indicated by a high condition index of 80.9 (>50).
  • VIF scores for some variables are also high (>=10) indicating collinearity.
  • To deal with multicollinearity, remove variables with VIF scores greater than or equal to 10: FirSemCredit, FirSemEnroll, FirSemApprove, SecSemCredit, SecSemEnroll, SecSemApprove.

4.4.3 Logistic Regression Model Evaluation:

  • From the report, out of 405 students who are at risk of dropping out (Target 1), the model correctly identified 280 (true positives), but incorrectly predicted that 125 (false negatives) would not drop out. On the other hand, out of 921 students who are not at risk of dropping out (Target 0), the model correctly identified 875 (true negatives), but incorrectly predicted that 46 (false positives) would drop out.
  • The overall accuracy of the model is 0.8697, which means that 87% of the predictions made by the model were correct.
  • The sensitivity of the model, which measures the proportion of true positives that were correctly identified, is 0.9501. This means that the model is able to correctly identify 95% of the students who are at risk of dropping out.
  • The specificity of the model, which measures the proportion of true negatives that were correctly identified, is 0.6880. This means that the model correctly identifies only 68.8% of the students who are not at risk of dropping out.
  • The positive predictive value (PPV) of the model is 0.8733, which means that out of all the students that the model predicted as being at risk of dropping out, 87.3% actually dropped out.
  • The negative predictive value (NPV) of the model is 0.8589, which means that out of all the students that the model predicted as not being at risk of dropping out, 85.9% did not drop out.
  • Overall, this confusion matrix suggests that the model is better at identifying students who are at risk of dropping out than students who are not at risk of dropping out. However, there is still room for improvement, especially in terms of increasing the specificity of the model.

The specificity (true negative rate) of the model is 0.63, indicating that the model correctly identifies only 63% of the students who are likely to graduate. The positive predictive value (PPV) of the model is 0.84, meaning that when the model predicts a student is at risk of dropping out, there is an 84% chance that the prediction is correct. The negative predictive value (NPV) of the model is 0.89, indicating that when the model predicts a student will graduate, there is a 89% chance that the prediction is correct.
  • In summary, the decision tree model has performed reasonably well in identifying students who are at risk of dropping out. However, the model has a relatively low specificity, meaning that it may identify some students as being at risk of dropping out when they are likely to graduate. This could result in unnecessary interventions and resources being allocated to these students. Therefore, the model may need further refinement or the use of additional variables to improve its performance.

4.5.5 Decision Tree Classification Insight:

  • The decision tree model has a split on the second semester grade variable where students who scored 10 or higher are directed to one branch and those who scored less than 10 are directed to the other branch.

  • For the branch where the student scored 10 or higher, the model splits again based on whether the student paid their tuition fees on time or not. If the student paid on time, the model predicts that the student will graduate. If not, the model predicts that the student might drop out.

  • For the branch where the student scored less than 10, the model splits again based on whether the student took less than 3 courses or 3 or more courses during the second semester. If the student took less than 3 courses, the model predicts that the student might have a chance to drop out. If the student took 3 or more courses and paid their tuition fees on time, the model predicts that the student will graduate. If not, the model predicts that the student might drop out.

In this case, the model predicted 41 true negatives, 153 false positives, 56 false negatives, and 280 true positives. - The accuracy of the model is around 84%, which means that the model is correct in predicting the outcome for 84% of the students in the dataset. The sensitivity and specificity values are 0.94 and 0.67, respectively. These values show that the model is good at correctly predicting the students who are dropouts (high sensitivity) but not very good at identifying the students who are not dropouts (low specificity).

  • The positive predictive value (PPV) is around 87%, which means that when the model predicts that a student is a dropout, there is an 87% chance that the student is actually a dropout.
  • The negative predictive value (NPV) is around 83%, which means that when the model predicts that a student is not a dropout, there is an 83% chance that the student is actually not a dropout.
  • Overall, the model seems to perform well in identifying student dropouts with a relatively high accuracy and PPV. However, there is room for improvement in terms of specificity and NPV.

Based on the analysis presented, it can be concluded that the logistic regression and random forest models are able to predict the likelihood of a student dropping out of college. The random forest model had an accuracy of 88.33% and a sensitivity of 96.74%, but a high false negative rate, indicating that it is better at predicting non-dropouts than dropouts.

The effect of socioeconomic factors on student success and dropout rates is a complex issue that requires a multifaceted approach. Here are some general recommendations that institutions could consider:

  • Institutions should focus on addressing the achievement gap by implementing programs and initiatives that help students from disadvantaged backgrounds succeed academically. This could include providing extra academic support, mentorship, and counseling services.

This could involve offering more diverse course offerings, providing opportunities for students to engage in extracurricular activities, and creating a campus culture that values diversity and inclusivity.
  • Improve data collection and analysis: Institutions should improve their data collection and analysis methods to better understand the impact of socioeconomic factors on student success and dropout rates. This could involve using more advanced statistical techniques to analyze large datasets.
  • Overall, addressing the impact of socioeconomic factors on student success and dropout rates requires a comprehensive approach that involves data analysis, targeted interventions, and a commitment to creating an inclusive and supportive learning environment.
